1 Abstract

In this document, multivariate regression methods (linear and polynomial estimators) have been tested to obtain the best estimation of the seasonal mean precipitation in the Valencian Community (Spain). Altitude and geographical coordinates (XUTM and YUTM) as well as the product between them were considered for further possible inclusion into the multivariate estimators. Firstly, some R functions are shown that allow the data to be imported and represented graphically or by means of a map. Some tools for a first descriptive analysis are also shown. Several multiple regression models are shown in order to assess the correct choice of explanatory variables, seeing the percentage of variability of the response variable that has been explained by the adjusted regression model. Each model comes with a study of residuals, assessing the appropriateness of a possible inclusion of new terms for these verify the assumption of linearity (zero mean), normality and homoscedasticity (constant variance).

2 Objectives

The objectives of this work are the following:

-Introduce to data analysis and spatial data manipulation in R

-Introduce to descriptive data analysis using R.

-Perform a descriptive analysis of an environmental data set based on precipitation data.

-Introduce to multivariate regression analysis using R.

-Determine the optimal multivariate polinomial regression function to predict seasonal mean precipitation using geographic and topographic variables.

-Introduce to dignosis of multivariate regression analysis using R.

  • Determine the accuracy of the estimation and prediction of multivariate lineal regression and multivariate polynomial regression models.

  • Study if the basic hypotheses of the multivariate lineal regression model are verified by analyzing the residuals and propose alternatives if it is not so.

-To propose models to jointly analyze the influence of several quantitative variables on a phenomenon to be studied.

3 Introduction

Rainfall data (daily, monthly, seasonally, annually,.) are gathered in meteorological stations spatially distributed in the territory at variable distances. A common problem consists on how to extrapolate those point data to the rest of the territory to generate rainfall maps at different scales. The spatial pattern of precipitation is a complex variable that strongly depends on other geographic and topographic factors. For this purpose, multivariate linear regression have been used in this document, in order to predict rainfall in other spatial coordinates of the territory. We focus on analysing an environmental data set which contains mean precipitation data from different available meteorological stations in the Valencian Community (CV) and its surroundings, located to the eastern Spanish Mediterranean coast. Such precipitation data comes from the raingauges of the National Institute of Meteorology network (AEMET in spanish), grouped into monthly means for the period of 1960-2005 (Portalés et al. 2010).

The analysis are carried out using the statistical and programming software R (R Core Team 2019), and this practical work serves as a practical introduction to data analysis and spatial data manipulation in R (Bivand et al. 2008). In this context “spatial data” refers to data about geographical locations. If you have not worked with R before, you can have a look at a brief introduction to R in (Venables et al. 2009).

This document performs a descriptive analysis of the data set, response and input (co-variables) variables, and performs linear regression analysis (Seber and Lee 2012; Gelman, Hill, and Vehtari 2020) on the data. The variables that form the data set are imported into R and are descriptively analyzed showing their histograms and summary statistics. Finally, several linear regression analysis are performed to relate a precipitation variable to the input variables, using different functional forms of the input variables

4.2 Study area and data set.

The study area corresponds to the Valencian Community (CV), Spain, and its surroundings, which is a Mediterranean coastal zone located in eastern Spain with an area of 23,255 Km2. It contains a mountainous area where the highest altitudes are about 1800 m. There exists a littoral plain region, principally constituted by floodplains and alluvial fans, and a coastline formed by smooth beaches and coastal lagoons.

4.2.1 Borders of the Valencian Community

The boundaries of the CV are provided by a shape file. If needed, we might have a look at the help page of the R command readOGR which loads a shape point file into R (Bivand et al. 2008). Notice that the following command line is commented, please uncomment it if you want to consult the command help page.

# help(readOGR)

With the following command line the polygons shape file cv containing the borders of the CV is converted to the spatial-polygons R-object lim_cv.

getwd()
lim_cv <- readOGR(dsn="Datos_cp4", layer="cv")

A summary of the structure and content of the generated spatial-polygons R-object lim_cv can be seen by using the R command str. Briefly, the object lim_cv is an object of R-class SpatialPoligonsDataFrame and has 5 slots: data, polygons, plotOrder, bbox and proj4string. The slot polygons contains a list with all the multipolygons (a multipolygon is of R-class Polygons). In this case, lim_cv contains only one multipolygon, and it is formed by two single polygons (a single polygon is of R-class Polygon). The slot data contains a table (data.frame) with the attributes (variables) associated to every one of the multipolygons. In this case, there is only one attribute, which is the identifier (PROVIN_ID) of the multipolygons. The slot bbox is a 2 \(\times\) 2 matrix with the 4 vertices of the boundary box of the geometrical data. And the slot proj4string specifies the coordinate reference system. In this case, no reference system is specified for the coordinates.

See Bivand et al. (2008) for a detalied explanation of the structure and manipulation of spatial-class objects in R.

4.3 Observational data

The observational data set consists in precipitation observations and associated attributes of the observed locations as the spatial coordinates and the elevation. Thus, data set contains mean precipitation data for the period of 1960-2005 in 212 meteorological stations of the CV. Our study considers seasonal temporal scales. Thus, monthly rainfall means were grouped into the following variables: spring (spring: March, April, May), summer (summer: June, July, August), autumn (autumn: September, October, November), and winter (winter: December, January, February). annual contains the mean annual precipitation in each meteorological observatory.

4.3.1 Precipitation variables

The precipitation variables as well as the spatial coordinates and the elevation of the observed points are provided by a shape file. The points shape file precip_seasonal which contains the data is read and converted to the spatial-points R-object dat by using the command readOGR.

dat <- readOGR(dsn="Datos_cp4", layer="precip_seasonal", integer64="warn.loss")

Next we can see a summary of the structure and content of the object dat. dat is an object of R-class SpatialPointsDataFrame and has 5 slots: data, coords.nrs, coords, bbox and proj4string. The slot data contains a table (data.frame) with 16 attributes or variables associated to the 212 observations. Among others, it has the seasonal precipitation variables, annual, spring, summer, autumn and winter, the altitud variable ALTITUD of the observed locations, and two spatial coordinates X and Y of the observed locations. The slot coords is a two-column matrix which also contains the two spatial coordinates X and Y of the observed locations. The slot bbox contains the boundary box for the spatial points. And the slot proj4string specifies the coordinate reference system.

4.4 Multivariate regression models

Mutivariate linear regression (MLR) (Seber and Lee 2012; Gelman, Hill, and Vehtari 2020) aims to fit a parametric linear function from data with some Gaussian noise. Within the MLR procedure, a precipitation variable in a location will be predicted by K continuous attributes in the same location using a linear function, considering the information available at all estimation points. The Method of Least Square Value(LSV) is used in this document in order to estimate coefficients of the linear function, at which the sum of the squares of errors between observed and predicted values is taken to be minimum. Polynomial Regression is a model used when the relation between the response variable and independent variables has a curvilinear structure. A Second Order Multiple Polynomial Regression can be expressed as:

\[\begin{align*} Y_i = &\: \beta_0 + \beta_1 X_{1i} + \beta_2 X_{2i} + \beta_{11} X^2_{1i} + \beta_{22} X^2_{2i} + \beta_{12} X_{1i} X_{2i} + \epsilon_i,\\ \epsilon_i \sim &\: \mathrm{Normal}(0,\sigma^2), \end{align*}\]

with:

\(i=1,\dots,n\), for \(n\) observations,

\(\epsilon_i\) is the Gaussian noise for the observation \(i\) where \(\sigma^2\) is the variance of the Gaussian noise,

\(\beta_1\) and \(\beta_2\) are called as linear effect parameters,

\(\beta_{11}\) and \(\beta_{22}\) are called as quadratic effect parameters,

\(\beta_{12}\) is called as interaction effect parameter.

In this section, some multivariate linear and polynomial regresion models are carried out to learn a function of the input variables from the spring precipitation data variable. We use the QR decomposition method implemented in the command lm of the R-package stats to fit the regression models. Some graphs (diagnosis plots) are represented using R functions to check if the model residuals \(\epsilon_i\) follow a normal distribution (normality hypothesis), with a zero mean (linearity) and constant variance (homoscedasticity).

4.4.1 Model 1

This model relates the spring precipitation variable spring to a linear function of the altitude input variable ALTITUD and some additive Gaussian noise.

\[\begin{align*} Y^{spring}_i = &\: \beta_0 + \beta_1 X^{altitud}_i + \epsilon_i, \\ \epsilon_i \sim &\: \mathrm{Normal}(0,\sigma^2), \end{align*}\] with \(i=1,\dots,n\), for \(n\) observations, and \(\epsilon_i\) is the Gaussian noise for the observation \(i\) where \(\sigma^2\) is the variance of the Gaussian noise.

4.4.1.1 Model adjustment

By using the R command lm, a linear regression analysis on the spring precipitation variable spring as a function of the altitude variable ALTITUD is performed. A summary of the results of the fitted model can be seen by means of the R command summary.

m1 <- lm(spring ~ ALTITUD, data=dat@data)
summary(m1)
## 
## Call:
## lm(formula = spring ~ ALTITUD, data = dat@data)
## 
## Residuals:
##     Min      1Q  Median      3Q     Max 
## -58.571 -19.813  -2.976  14.107  90.742 
## 
## Coefficients:
##              Estimate Std. Error t value Pr(>|t|)    
## (Intercept) 1.193e+02  3.308e+00  36.062  < 2e-16 ***
## ALTITUD     2.432e-02  5.964e-03   4.078 6.45e-05 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1

## F-statistic: 16.63 on 1 and 210 DF,  p-value: 6.45e-05

The statistic R-squared is a measure of the amount of variablity explained by the model. For this model, the R-squared resulted around 0.07, which means that this model explains only the small quantity of 7% of the original variability of the spring precipitation variable.

Figure 4.5 shows the model expected spring precipitation and the data points.

Figure 4.6: Histograms of the model residuals (left) and spring precipitation variable (right) (from results provided by model 1).

Figure 4.7 shows a plot of the model residuals against the spring precipitation variable. For a optimal fit, model residuals should be distributed randomly around the horizontal zero line. In this case, residuals are far from this optimal situation, which means that there is still much of the spring precipitation variable to be explained by the model, and that the latent linear function of the altitud variable is a poor function proposal.

# plot settings (see help(par))
par(mfrow=c(1,1), mai=c(0.6, 0.6, 0.2, 0.2), mgp=c(1.5, 0.5, 0), cex.lab=0.75, cex.main=0.75, cex.axis=0.75)

# plot
plot(dat@data$spring, m1$residuals, asp=1, ylab="residual", cex=0.5)
abline(h=0, col="blue", lty=2)

Figure 4.7: Plot of the model residuals vs the spring precipitation observations (from results provided by model 1).

4.4.2 Model 2

This model relates the spring precipitation variable spring to a linear function of the altitude variable ALTITUD and the spatial coordinates X and Y.

\[\begin{align*} Y^{spring}_i = &\: \beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot X^{altitude}_i + \beta_2 \cdot X^{XUTM}_i + \beta_3 \cdot X^{YUTM}_i + \epsilon_i, \\ \epsilon_i \sim &\: \mathrm{Normal}(0,\sigma^2). \end{align*}\]

with \(i=1,\dots,n\), for \(n\) observations, and \(\epsilon_i\) is the Gaussian noise for the observation \(i\) where \(\sigma^2\) is the variance of the Gaussian noise.

4.4.2.1 Model adjustment

By using the R command lm, a linear regression analysis on the spring precipitation variable spring as a function of the altitude variable ALTITUD is performed. A summary of the results of the fitted model can be seen by means of the R command summary.

Linear regression analysis on the spring precipitation spring as a function of the altitude variable ALTITUD and the spatial coordinates X and Y, and a summary of the results of the fitted model. with \(i=1,\dots,n\), for \(n\) observations, and \(\epsilon_i\) is the Gaussian noise for the observation \(i\) where \(\sigma^2\) is the variance of the Gaussian noise.

Formulate, fit and make the diagnosis of the following model which relates the autumn precipitation variable autumn to the altitude variable altitud, the spatial coordinates X and Y, and the interaction between the spatial coordinates X and Y.

\[\begin{align*} Y^{autumn}_i = &\:\beta_0 + \beta_1 \cdot X^{altitud}_i + \beta_2 \cdot X^{Xutm}_i + \beta_3 \cdot X^{Yutm}_i + \beta_4 \cdot X^{Xutm}_i \cdot X^{Yutm}_i + \epsilon_i, \\ \epsilon_i \sim &\: \mathrm{Normal}(0,\sigma^2). \end{align*}\]

with \(i=1,\dots,n\), for \(n\) observations, and \(\epsilon_i\) is the Gaussian noise for the observation \(i\) where \(\sigma^2\) is the variance of the Gaussian noise.

5 Conclussion

Multiple regression should be rejected as an unreliable model to interpolate the rainfall variable in spring, using altitude and geographical coordinates as independent variables if residuals are not treated in further analysis. It has been shown how the inclusion of new terms (quadratic and interaction) can increase the percentage of variance explained by the model. However, the residuals do not meet the normality hypotheses with an average equal to zero and constant variance. Thus, we should correct the residuals of that model using more independent variables in the regression model. If this is not possible, other techniques should be used to estimate spring precipitation, which will be the subject of other documents in this series.

Instead, summer model explains adequately the 85% of the rainfall variability with altitude, XUTM and YUTM, considering the interaction between these geographical coordinates, being all coefficients in the model statistically significant. The analysis of the residues has allowed detecting the existence of outliers in the sample. This study proves that precipitation in the Valencian Community (Spain) has a seasonal behavior, which could be predicted in summer taking into account the altitude of each point and its geographical position. This document has served to describe the use of some functions of the R program to calculate and analyze all these results, not only the statistical ones, but also to capture the information provided by raster files and shape files.
